The diagnostic block you included is doing exactly what it's supposed to do, and it points directly to the root of the problem.

Because the simple inline formula (own_home ~ origin_region) succeeded, but your complex models failed across the board, the issue isn't the subsetting or the survey design. It is a singularity (perfect collinearity) caused by one of your control variables crashing the regression algorithm.

The Culprit: yiu_missing
In your V7 variable engineering chunk, you updated the foreign_born definition to strictly require a valid number of years lived in the U.S.:
foreign_born = as.integer(!is.na(years_in_us) & years_in_us > 0 ...)

By doing this, you guarantee that every single respondent who makes it into your analytic sample has a valid years_in_us value. Consequently, there are zero missing values for this variable in your subset.

Because nobody is missing this data, your yiu_missing indicator variable is a constant 0 for the entire scf_fb subset. When you pass a constant variable into a GLM or OLS regression, the math cannot compute the variance, causing the model to throw the "Too few successful implicate-level models to pool" error and halt.

The Fix
Since your sample is now strictly filtered to those with valid duration data, you no longer need the missing-indicator method. You can simply use the raw years_in_us variable in your model formulas.

Here are the two chunks you need to update to get everything compiling correctly.

1. Update h1-model-helper
Remove the missing-indicator variables from your baseline and full specification strings, replacing them with years_in_us.

